South African Stocks Advance, Led by AngloGold, Gold Fields, BHP Billiton

-- B y   C a r l i   L o u r e n s   a n d   L a u r e n   v a n   d e r   W e s t h u i z e n
-- 
2011-05-13T15:58:20Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-13/stocks-in-south-africa-advance-led-by-anglo-american-bhp-billiton-sasol.html
The FTSE/JSE  Africa  All Share Index
rose 278.10, or 0.9 percent, to 31,959.93 at the 5 p.m. close in
Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today:  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (ANG)  , Africa’s biggest gold
producer, rose 5.70 rand, or 1.9 percent, to 310.40 rand,
snapping two days of declines, as the local-currency price of
bullion rose to a record.  Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI)  , the
continent’s second-biggest producer of the metal, climbed 2.39
rand, or 2.2 percent, to 108.99 rand.  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s biggest mining
company, rose for the first day in three, adding 2.57 rand, or 1
percent, to 267.62 rand, as the price of copper, lead, nickel
and zinc increased on the London Metal Exchange.  Anglo American
Plc (AGL)  , the biggest investor in South African mining,
advanced 4.50 rand, or 1.4 percent, to 333 rand.  Gold One International Ltd. (GDO)  , a gold producer,
halted trading of its stock in Johannesburg and Sydney pending a
May 16 announcement by the company of a takeover transaction.
The shares gained 5 cents, or 1.5 percent, to 3.35 rand
yesterday.  Sasol Ltd. (SOL)  , the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, climbed 5.25 rand, or 1.5 percent, to 360.19
rand as the price of oil gained as much as 1.8 percent.  UCS Group Ltd. (UCS)  , the information technology company
selling some of its units to Business Connexion Group (BCX SJ),
rose 5.44 cents, or 15 percent, to 42 cents. UCS said a third
party has expressed interest in purchasing one of the units. The
stock started trading without the right to its dividends.  To contact the reporters on this story:
